data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based calls, so this throws at runtime.

## Fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force binding to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `array.Reverse()` (resolves to the in-place `Span` extension returning `void` instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`). Apply the same pattern: `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` or `arr.AsEnumerable().Reverse()`.
